 export,, was\nlargely nullified l?y tbe confirmed\nreport that France had found\nAmerican wheat prices too high and\nhad purchased its requirements In\nArgentina at 15c? less This controverted\nthe claims of the previous\nday that there was only a slight difference.\nit being a matter of how\nthe different ones figured. Traders\nloaded up early and sold out later,\nmaking a decline of 234c on March\nand 3c on May. with the inside\n$1.66*4 for March and $1.57Me for\nMay.\nGreen bugs reports from the\nSouthwest were more numerous,\nwith insects at work in Oklahoma\nand Southern Kansas. Chicago men\nhack fnfm a run through Kansas\nsay the weather is warm and dry\nand dusty, with the wheal! up In\npinches and being pastured. This\nwas confirmed by the Kansas State\nweather report saying that Southern\nKansas needed rain.\nArgentina differences for the\nweek were 1,269,000 bushels, compared\nwith 4.995.000 bushels last\nyear, and for the year to date aegregate\n10.612,000 bushels compared\nwith 46.571.000 bushels last year.\nExport clearances from this country\nfor the day were 742.000 bushels.\nPrimary arrivals continue to exceed\nlast year's, despite reduced farmers'\nsales.\nFollowing: an* today'* quotation* on rrain\nand provisions:\nWbea t?\nOpen High I..?w rIns?\nMarch? 1 1.60 l 106*4\nMay l.?ij 1.6??, l.Slfc IM%\nCorn?\nMar 71% .71 7?% 70%\nJul/ \"iV? .73% 12% .72%\nOat*?\nMar 4\"% .4.-.% .44% .44%\nJuly 4C% 10% .4.-,% .45%\nPork\nMay 22.25 22 3.'# 2I.U 21.95\nL?nl?\nMay 12.30 12.35 12.12 12.17\n(Quotations furnished by W. B. Hibba k\nCo., Member a Chicago Board of Trade.)\nJ\nCHARLES C. GLOVER\nWM. J. FLATHER jj?\nVice President jfrjl\nJOSHUA EVANS. lf. kjij i t JjHg\nVice Fr?iid?nt M 1 U|l\nT^HE1 SECRET of gai\nI* young is working\ngoal always before you\nIt's the little side-steps tha\nand money, and retard yo\\\nIf you would gain distinct\npation while still young,\nIf you would be a man of 1\nto get the most enjoyment\na comfortable home, SAV1\nII To young m